A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the Mediterranean migration crisis.
First, Europe and the international community are applying a cruelly unsuitable system for the protection of the most vulnerable migrants.
Second, in the face of the inefficiency of this system, populist actors continue to exploit fears in order to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies whose construction has required some 70 years of determined efforts.
This is why it is essential that this year a genuinely active initiative be undertaken at the European and global levels.
In September, UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at building a solid global system for the protection of the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let us hope that States will be ready to commit in a concrete and lasting manner.
This necessary commitment was cruelly lacking during the year 2015.
In fact, the international community would have been able to limit the severity of last year's crisis if it had provided even the most modest support to countries on the front line – Turkey, Lebanon and Jordan – which together host no fewer than four million refugees.
With only about 10 billion €, these countries would have been better able to provide housing, food and education to the refugees, thus reducing the temptation to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany alone up to 21 billion € every year in the years to come.
But the financial implications of the crisis are in no way comparable to its human and political cost.
More than one million people risked their lives last year crossing the Mediterranean, enduring afterwards an exhausting journey through the Balkans.
Nearly 4,000 migrants lost their lives there, while many European countries turned their backs on the survivors by refusing to grant them refuge.
The most cynical political actors have mercilessly exploited citizens' fears, promoting an odious nationalist vision, either ignoring or distorting the life experiences of migrants.
In the United States, for example, not a single one of the 780,000 refugees settled since September 11, 2001, has committed any terrorist act.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more in taxes than they receive in social benefits.
And yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with taking political power in certain European countries, and are currently gaining support even within former liberal strongholds.
Anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success also leads traditional parties to promote an immigration-hostile policy themselves.
This situation has significantly undermined European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at dealing with the million refugees who arrived on its coasts has only managed to "relocate" 190 of them.
Border controls in six countries belonging to the Schengen area have been reinstated, at least temporarily.
In the eyes of the rest of the world, the EU now appears nationalist and incompetent.
Of course, resolving this crisis concerns not only Europe; responsibility cannot be defined merely by geographical proximity.
Whatever the case, the EU is undoubtedly facing today a threat to its own existence, which it will only be able to overcome by firmly demonstrating the solidarity and international leadership it is capable of.
This is why it is up to the member states to take the initiative in proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority is to establish legal and secure channels allowing refugees to reach Europe.
It is not a matter of asserting that every migrant in difficulty must be welcomed.
Nevertheless, it is up to the EU to be more systematically generous in determining the number of refugees to welcome, and to use orderly mechanisms aimed at facilitating their entry.
Such a system would allow the protection of migrants while safeguarding Europe (through the possibility of fully examining applications).
Going beyond an approach aiming to dissuade asylum seekers from risking their lives by crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would allow projecting an image of solidarity to frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
Equally important, this approach would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to the efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of 2016: building a solid global system for the protection of refugees and vulnerable migrants.
This objective will first require that more countries accept to host refugees.
In recent years, the United Nations Refugee Agency has only managed to resettle less than 75 00HYPERLINK "http://www.unhcr.org/559ce97f9.html" 0 of the approximately 20 million annual refugees.
Several million of them end up in a situation of protracted migration, with an average duration estimated at 25 years, trapped in a kind of purgatory and uncertain about the day of a possible return to their country.
In 2016, it is necessary that developed countries agree to host a cumulative number close to one million refugees each year, either through their resettlement, or by granting them a humanitarian, student, professional, or other visa.
Canada having stated that it would host alone 50,000 Syrian refugees this year, this is a clearly achievable goal.
At the same time, the international community will have to support the integration of refugees in major host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
As things stand, these countries only receive a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually needed per refugee for housing, food, care, education, and vocational training during the first years of settlement.
And these figures do not take into account the necessary cost of building or upgrading infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for example, water supply systems are suffering from the pressure caused by the massive arrival of refugees.
In exchange for funding, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor markets, and civic institutions.
But effective integration of migrants will only be possible if European and other countries get rid of their prejudices regarding migrants.
If these migrants continue to be seen as a burden, or even as a threat to security, reactionary political forces will continue to gain ground, depriving newcomers of opportunities and transforming fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the other hand, if host countries manage to integrate migrants with enthusiasm, everyone will benefit – including these countries (notably through the inflow of money).
Last month, in Paris, the international community proved that it was capable of subordinating its national interests to a broader global objective: the fight against climate change.
In 2016, a similar effort is needed to build a better protection system for migrants.
This is a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies around the world.
